The paper focuses on Convolutional Neural Networks (ConvNets) and their ability to learn features in a locally scale-invariant manner. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of less parameters and less data to learn more discriminative features, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the problem of over-fitting, which is a common concern in Neural Networks, suggesting that it may belong to the Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses a modified MNIST dataset, which is a commonly used dataset in Natural Language Processing (NLP) and Computer Vision (CV), suggesting that it may also belong to the Computation and Language (cs.CL) sub-category.
